1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 {The Advance Variation. White immediately takes more
space on the kingside, but he also gives Black a target in the center since
the pawns are now immobilized.} 3... c5 {
Black lashes out at the base of White's central pawn chain.} 4. c3 {Understanda
bly, White stabilizes his pawn chain. This is not White's only move, but it is
his most common move.} 4... Qb6 {In this system, Black delays the move ... Nc6
because he has a very interesting plan in mind.} 5. Nf3 {White plays a natural
developing move, putting this Knight on its best square. It is not clear yet
where the other Knight should go, so White usually leaves it on b1 for a while.
} 5... Bd7 {A key move in Black's plan. Note that Black delays ...Nc6 -- not a
bad move in itself -- for the sake of a Bishop maneuver.} 6. Bd3 {White continu
es to develop. This is probably the best square for White's Bishop, and after
that, he can castle. Then it will be time to see what Black has done and to
choose places for his other pieces.} 6... Bb5 {Black plays to swap off his bad
Bishop for White's good one -- a simple and sound positional plan.} 7. O-O {
White reasons that he might as well continue developing.} 7... Bxd3 {
As advertised!} 8. Qxd3 {There is, of course, no choice.} 8... Qa6 $1 {
Now that those Bishops are off, Black would love to trade Queens as well.} 9.
Qxa6 {White goes along with Black's plan.} 9... Nxa6 {This position is very
instructive. Black has less space, but with his bad Bishop exchanged for
White's good one and with Queens off the board, space does not matter much.
More importantly, Black's pieces work together well here. If this does not
seem obvious, watch the next dozen moves or so carefully.} 10. Be3 Rc8 {
The c-file might come open or it might not, but overprotecting the pawn at c5
gives Black the freedom to develop his kingside with ...Ne7 without losing a
pawn on c5.} 11. Nbd2 {Because he has taken away the best square for this
Knight by playing c3, White has to bring it out to this more awkward square.
But at least now his Rooks are connected.} 11... Ne7 {
As advertised. Notice how the Rook on c8 plays a key role defending c5.} 12.
Nb3 {White adds a new attacker to the pawn on c5.} 12... Nf5 $1 {And Black adds
a defender by clearing this Knight out of the path of the Bishop on f8.} 13.
Rfe1 {White is somewhat at a loss for a good move. The Rook is not really well
placed here, but it isn't at all clear where the Rooks belong.} 13... c4 $1 {
Normally, Black would be reluctant to lock things up with ... c4 like this.
But here, there are several considerations that favor ...c4. (1) Pressure on
d4 is not going to do any good: White has that point protected four ways. (2)
Sealing the pawn structure with ...c4 makes White's bad Bishop even worse and
Black's good Bishop even better. (3) There will be a new pawn break at b4.} 14.
Nbd2 Be7 {Just because the position is closed, it does not follow that Black
should not develop his pieces.} 15. g4 {White panics. This is a significant
turning point in the game, because the net effect of White's pawn push will be
that the kingside -- the side where White has more space -- becomes completely
blockaded.} 15... Nxe3 {Although this was White's bad Bishop, Black correctly
sees that he will have an even easier time making the ...b4 break if he trades
here.} 16. Rxe3 b5 {Preparing for ...b4.} 17. a3 {
White tries to prevent ...b4. But in the long run, he cannot stop it.} 17...
Nc7 {Black intends ...a5 and ultimately, at the right time, ...b4. So he gets
the Knight out of the a-pawn's way.} 18. Kg2 (18. a4 {would of course be met by
} 18... b4 {here, denying White an open a-file and preparing to occupy the
b-file and then trade pawns.}) 18... Kd7 {Black wants his Rooks connected.
Notice that he has the square g5 under control: White will not be able to win
a pawn with Ng5 forking h7 and f7.} 19. Kg3 a5 {
Black gradually expands on the queenside, preparing the ...b4 breakthrough.}
20. h4 {White tries to generate some counterplay of his own on the kingside.
It is instructive to see how Black nips this plan in the bud.} 20... h5 $1 21.
g5 g6 $1 {Now the kingside is completely locked up, so Black can turn his
attention to the queenside, where he has the breakthrough idea ...b4.} 22. Ne1
b4 {If White ignores this pawn, Black will trade on a3 and then bring his
Rooks to the b-file.} 23. axb4 axb4 {For just a moment, White has an open
a-file. But his Rooks are so clumsily placed -- the Rook on e3 cannot help the
Rook on a1 -- that Black will very quickly take over the file himself.} 24.
Nef3 {The Knight looks nice there, but where is he going?} ({
Perhaps White should try} 24. Rf3 {
here. But Black can keep everything under control with} 24... Rhf8 25. Ng2 Ra8
26. Rxa8 Nxa8 27. Ne3 Nb6 $15) 24... Ra8 $1 {Black has the pawn on b4 defended,
so he leaves the tension in the position and neutralizes White's control of
the a-file.} (24... bxc3 25. bxc3 {
would make it easier for White to defend the pawn at c3 -- his only weakness.})
25. Ree1 Nb5 $1 {Putting more pressure on c3.} 26. Rxa8 (26. Reb1 {
might be best, but it is very difficult for White after} 26... bxc3 27. bxc3
Kc6 $1 28. Rxa8 Rxa8 29. Rc1 Ra2 $17) 26... Rxa8 {Now Black has complete
control of the a-file in addition to his pressure against c3.} 27. cxb4 {
After this move, both d4 and b2 are weak.} (27. Rc1 Ra2 {
forces White to capture on b4 anyway, and after} 28. cxb4 Rxb2 $1 $19 {
White is losing a pawn.}) 27... Bxb4 28. Rb1 {This move loses a vital pawn,
but White was in serious difficulties in any event.} 28... Bxd2 $1 29. Nxd2
Nxd4 {Black is just one pawn up, but all of his pawns are welded into a single
unit, defended from f7 -- a square White can only dream of attacking.
Meanwhile, White's pawns are too far advanced and therefore weak. White cannot
survive for long here.} 30. f4 Ra2 {
Now the threat is 32...c3 33.bxc3 Nf5+! and 34...Rxd2.} 31. Kf2 Nf5 {Now the pa
wn on h4 falls. This is a nice example of how an overextended pawn formation
becomes vulnerable in the endgame. Compare Black's pawn structure --
everything is anchored by the pawn at f7, which White has no way to attack.}
32. Ke2 Nxh4 {Now Black has two extra pawns, one on each side of the board. He
can (and should) take his time winning, since White cannot undertake anything
constructive.} 33. b4 $2 {A final error in a lost position.} 33... c3 {
White resigns. A very instructive game from Volkov!} 0-1

