1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 Bb5 $1 {GM Volkov is
very fond of this variation, which gets rid of Black's positional problem
piece in record time.} 7. O-O Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Qa6 {Offering a Queen exchange,
which White is understandably reluctant to accept. With Queens off, White's
space advantage will mean less and his bad Bishop will mean more.} 9. Qd1 {
White declines the swap. What can Black do now?} 9... Nd7 {
Very instructive. This Knight is headed for c4!} (9... Nc6 {
is a more typical move, but Volkov has an interesting plan in mind.}) 10. Na3
cxd4 11. cxd4 Bxa3 $5 {It is always an interesting question whether Black
should give up his good Bishop in order to double and isolate White's pawns.
The danger is that White's remaining Bishop may hop onto the a3-f8 diagonal,
causing some trouble.} 12. bxa3 {One other point of the exchange on a3 is that
now White cannot protect the c4 square with a pawn -- the pawn cannot get to
b3 anymore.} 12... Ne7 {
Black completes his development before he undertakes any other plans.} 13. a4 {
White is trying to get his Bishop on to that diagonal as fast as possible.
Black, on the other hand, has screened it and now castles -- just intime!}
13... O-O {Phew!} 14. Ba3 {
White hits the undefended Knight, causing Black to pause for a moment.} 14...
Rfe8 {Unpinning and defending the Knight.} 15. Qb3 {Now Black needs to get his
Knights, in particular, to more active squares. One square that cries out for
a Knight is c4, a square from which it cannot be chased by a pawn, since White
no longer has a b-pawn. This explains the following maneuver. Notice that the
Knight maneuver solves what might otherwise be a pressing practical decision
-- should Black occupy the c-file right away? The answer is that he does not
need to, since the Knight on c4 will provide perfect cover for a buildup of
heavy pieces on that file.} 15... Nb6 $1 {Heading to the outpost!} 16. Rfc1 Nc4
$1 ({A weak player might be tempted to win White's front a-pawn here. But the
joy would be short-lived:} 16... Qxa4 17. Qxa4 Nxa4 18. Rc7 $1 Nc6 19. Rb1 Nb6
20. Rxb7 {and White has regained the pawn -- a healthy pawn in exchange for
his sickly one at a4 -- and his active Rook is very annoying.}) 17. Rc2 Rac8 {
Black reinforces the Knight.} 18. Rac1 Rc6 {
Preparing to double up Rooks as soon as possible.} 19. Bc5 b6 {
Chasing the Bishop out of position.} 20. Bxe7 {White gives in and gets rid of
Black's Knight before it can jump to an annoying square like f5 or g6.} 20...
Rxe7 21. Qb5 {White would gladly exchange Queens here.} 21... Qc8 $1 {
Instead of trading and straightening out White's pawns, Black triples his
heavy pieces on the c-file.} 22. Nd2 {White puts more pressure on c4. Black
cannot take the Knight on d2 now because he would lose the Rook on c6.} 22...
Rec7 $1 {White has doubled on the c-file, but Black has tripled there!} 23.
Nxc4 Rxc4 24. Rxc4 Rxc4 25. Rxc4 {Don't stumble now!} 25... dxc4 $1 {The passed
c-pawn will be a huge asset, whereas White's d-pawn is backward and vulnerable.
The next few moves illustrate this vulnerability: Black ties down White's
Queen to the job of stopping the c-pawn from queening and then, with a threat
to the d-pawn, forces White's Queen backward into an even more unfavorable
position.} (25... Qxc4 $4 26. Qe8# {would be very disappointing.}) 26. Qb2 c3 {
White's King is so far away that there is no danger of this pawn's being
encircled and trapped.} 27. Qc2 {
White absolutely has to stop this pawn from advancing.} 27... Qc4 {
Now the threat is ...Qxd4.} 28. Qe4 {White fights back as hard as he can. Here,
he defends the pawn on d4 and sets up a threat of mate.} 28... Qd5 {An excellen
t practical decision. Black could also win with .. .f5, but that would require
more calculation in order to ensure that no accidents occur.} (28... f5 {
would also win, but it requires a bit more calculation to make sure that White
cannot snag a draw by perpetual check somehow.}) 29. Qd3 {White has managed to
keep d4 defended and to prevent the advance ...c2, but now something else
falls.} 29... Qxa2 $1 {
Back rank mate threats keep White from taking the pawn on c3.} 30. h3 (30. Qxc3
Qb1+ $1 {and Black gives checkmate next move.}) 30... Qxa4 $2 {
Black stumbles here and has to go through the trouble of winning all overagain.
} (30... c2 $1 $19 {is simple and efficient:} 31. Qd2 Qb1+ {etc.}) 31. Qxc3 Qd7
{Stopping mate on c8.} 32. Qc4 h6 {Black makes "Luft" (German for "air"),
which frees him to advance his queenside pawns with the support of his Queen
without worrying about getting mated.} 33. Kh2 g6 34. f4 a5 {Here they come.}
35. Qc3 a4 36. Qb4 Qa7 $1 {With the Queen behind the pawn, Black simply
threatens to ram it through. Notice that the Queen also defends the pawn on f7,
so even if White gets his Queen to f6, there is no hope of his getting a
perpetual check.} 37. Qa3 b5 {Now the pawn at a4 is defended twice, so Black's
Queen is free to pick off the pawn at d4.} 38. h4 Qxd4 39. Qe7 {
Pure desperation.} 39... Qxf4+ {White resigns} 0-1

