1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 Qb6 {Volkov's favorite idea in the
Advance French: trading Black's bad Bishop for White's good one.} 6. Bd3 Bb5 7.
dxc5 {Capturing here does not prevent the exchange of lightsquare Bishops.}
7... Bxc5 {Now Black is attacking f2, so White decides to castle in order to
defend that weak point.} 8. O-O Bxd3 {
Naturally enough, Black finishes the trade off.} 9. Qxd3 Qa6 {This sideways
move is quite common in the ...Bd7-b5 line. Black would be very happy to trade
Queens. A second point of the move is that now Black can play ...Ne7 without
losing a piece to b4, because now his Bishop can retreat to b6.} 10. Qd2 {
White decides not to allow the exchange of Queens.} 10... Nd7 {Since White has
no d-pawn in this position, Black builds up pressure against e5. In this line,
unlike many other French lines, this Knight often goes to d7 rather than to c6,
since on c6 it strikes at two squares (d4 and b4) that are off limits anyway
thanks to White's pawn on c3.} (10... Ne7 {
might be a little bit more accurate, since then Black can meet} 11. Qg5 {with}
11... Ng6 12. h4 Nd7 13. h5 f6 $1 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Qg4 Ne7 16. b4 Rg8 17. Qh3
Bd6 18. Re1 e5 $15 {with a good (albeit strange) position.}) 11. Qg5 Bf8 $1 {
Black does not want to create any pawn weaknesses by ...g6.} 12. Nbd2 Ne7 {
Heading for g6.} 13. b3 Ng6 {Now Black has so much pressure against the pawn
on e5 that White is committed to babysitting that pawn. This means that his
Queen cannot go wherever she might want to.} 14. c4 Be7 {Since Black wants to
castle, he moves the Bishop out in a way that gains a tempo by slapping
White's Queen.} 15. Qg3 O-O 16. Bb2 {White's Bishop does not actually stand
badly here, since he has rearranged his queenside pawns on light squares.} (16.
cxd5 exd5 $17 {Although Black's d-pawn is isolated, he stands better because
his pieces work together better than White's pieces do.}) 16... Ba3 {Black deci
des that he wants the extra space he can gain by forcing Bishops off the board.
} 17. Bxa3 Qxa3 18. cxd5 exd5 {Now Black has an isolated d-pawn, but he also
has the half-open e-file for adding pressure to White's e-pawn.} 19. h4 {
White threatens to chase Black's Knight away from g6.} 19... Rfe8 {But Black co
unters by attacking e4 a third time, which would allow the Knight to take the
e-pawn after all.} 20. Rae1 {White defends the pawn, but the cost is too high:
Black will not only annihilate the queenside but also pick up the Knight on d2
if the other Knight moves.} (20. Rfe1 Qb2 21. Reb1 Qc3 22. Rc1 Qa5 {Black has m
anaged to keep White's N/d2 under attack, and that means that the e-pawn is
doomed.} 23. Re1 Ngxe5 24. Nxe5 Nxe5 25. Rxe5 Qxd2 $17) 20... Qxa2 $1 21. h5 {
Plowing forward -- White perhaps missed what happens at the end of the tactics.
} 21... Ngxe5 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Qxd2 $1 {
Oops! Black not only regains the piece but also defends the pawn on d4.} 24.
Rfe1 Qxe1+ $1 {
Volkov knows that in this position, two Rooks are even stronger than a Queen.}
25. Rxe1 {White resigns} (25. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 26. Kh2 Re6 27. Qc7 Rb6 28. h6 Rxh6+
29. Kg1 Rb6 $19 {and Black should be able to win, though of course he must be
careful not to drop a Rook or get mated on the back rank!}) 0-1

