1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 Bb5 7. c4 $6 {When White
has a Bishop on d3, the move c4 is not so good, for reasons that Black now
makes plain.} 7... dxc4 $1 {This move hits the Bishop on d3, forcing it to
move. So White doesn't get the chance to play d5 under favorable circumstances.
} 8. Be4 Nc6 {Very simple.} (8... cxd4 {is also okay:} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Nxb5
Qxb5 11. Nc3 Qxe5 12. O-O Rc8 13. Re1 Qb8 $17) 9. O-O (9. dxc5 Bxc5 $19 {
Black is a pawn ahead and has a lead in development.}) (9. d5 exd5 10. Bxd5 Nb4
11. Be4 Rd8 12. Qe2 c3 $1 {Ouch! White's Queen is attacked.} 13. Qe3 Bd3 $1 {
Threatening ...Nc2+.} 14. Na3 cxb2 15. Bxb2 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nd3+ 17. Kf1 Qxb2 $19
{White has collapsed tactically.}) 9... Nxd4 10. Nc3 Bc6 11. a4 Ne7 {
This move is not bad, but it may not be best.} (11... Bxe4 $1 12. Nxe4 Rd8 $19
{The threat of ...Nb3, attacking both White's Rook and his Queen, hangs over
White's head.}) 12. a5 Qd8 {Black keeps his Queen lined up to support d4.} 13.
Be3 {White adds more pressure. What should Black do?} (13. a6 {
forces Black to be rather careful, as there are some traps:} 13... b5 14. Nxd4
cxd4 15. Bxc6+ Nxc6 16. Nxb5 Nxe5 $2 17. Qa4 $1 Qd7 $4 (17... Nd7 18. Qxc4 Bc5
19. Rd1 O-O 20. Nxd4 Qh4 $11) 18. Nc7+ $1 {Ouch!}) 13... Nef5 {
This is a decent move, but Black has other choices here as well.} (13... Bxe4
14. Nxe4 Nec6 $1 $17 {is nice for Black, who gets to untangle his pieces.}) 14.
Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Qe2 {
White would love to grab that pawn on c4, reducing his material deficit.} 15...
Qd3 $1 {This is a very nice way of defending the pawn.} 16. Rfd1 Qxe2 17. Nxe2
{Now the pawn on c4 is under no pressure at all, and Black can get back to the
business of completing his development.} 17... Be7 {Black reali zes that he
needs to complete his development. The Bishop on c6 prevents a Rook from
coming to d7, so Black can castle and activate his other Rook.} 18. Rd2 O-O 19.
Rad1 Nxe3 $1 {Black doubles and isolates White's e-pawns and grabs the
advantage of two Bishops vs two Knights.} 20. fxe3 Rfd8 $1 {Rooks off, please!}
21. Nf4 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 Rd8 23. Kf2 Bxf3 $1 {This forces off everything except a
Knight for White and a Bishop for Black. But Black's Bishop will be a
darksquare Bishop, and White has weak pawns on dark squares. So Black, who is
already two pawns ahead, will win some more material.} 24. Rxd8+ Bxd8 25. gxf3
Bxa5 {There are many ways to win now.} (25... Bc7 $1 26. Ne2 Bxe5 27. Nc3 {
and now the simplest line for Black is} 27... Bxc3 28. bxc3 e5 $19 {and White w
ill be helpless against ...b5 when Black can create passed pawns on both sides
of the board.}) 26. e4 Bc7 {White resigns. He cannot hold the pawn on e5, and
then the pawn on b2 is in danger of falling off as well.} 0-1

