1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 {The Russian GM Evgeny
Sveshnikov used the a3 idea in the Advance Variation of the French against the
standard Qb6/Nc6 setup. Here, White tries it against the Bd7-b5 plan. It turns
out that Black has enough defensive resources even in the sharpest line.} 6...
Bb5 $5 (6... cxd4 {may be a simpler way to play. After} 7. cxd4 Bb5 {Black gets
to carry out his intended exchange of Bishops without the risks associated
with White's plan of c4 and d5.}) 7. c4 $5 {One of White's principal ideas
against the ...Bd7-b5 plan is to break in the center with c4 and d5.} 7... dxc4
8. d5 {
This idea requires careful handling from Black, but Volkov is up to the task.}
8... Ne7 9. Nc3 (9. d6 {looks dangerous at first glance, but it turns out that
White gets very tangled up trying to defend the pawn on e5 after} 9... Ng6 10.
Nbd2 Nd7 11. Qe2 Qa5 {By pinning the N/d2, Black sets up the idea of ...
Bc6xf3 and ...Ngxe5. Yes, this is a slow plan, but the position is somewhat
blocked up, and once White loses the pawn on e5, the pawn on d6 is sure to
follow. And don't forget that White is already a pawn downhere!} 12. Qe3 Bc6
13. Bxc4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Ngxe5 15. Qxb7 Rb8 16. Qe4 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 Bxd6 {
Now Black is a pawn up, and if he can consolidate, he will win.} 18. O-O O-O
19. Rd1 Rfd8 20. Nf3 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Rxd8+ Qxd8 $19) 9... exd5 10. Nxd5
Qd8 11. Nc3 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Ba6 {Black is a pawn up here, though the pawn is
admittedly doubled and on an open file. More significantly, White's e-pawn is
easy to attack and difficult to defend, particularly since White's King is
stuck in the center.} 13. g3 Nbc6 14. Bg2 Ng6 {Piling up on the pawn.} 15. Bf4
O-O-O+ 16. Kc1 Nxf4 17. gxf4 Nd4 {Threatening a fork on b3.} (17... Be7 $1 {
first would control g5, preventing the idea in the next note. Then Black could
continue with ...Nd4 under even more favorable circumstances.}) 18. Kb1 $2 {
White merely reacts to the threatened fork and thereby misses his best chance
for counterplay.} (18. Ng5 $1 Rd7 19. Bd5 $1 {would come close to equalizing
for White here -- which is saying quite a bit, since White has been
positionally worse for some time. Black's best response is probably} 19... f6
20. Nf7 Rg8 21. Kb1 Be7 {with the idea} 22. Nd6+ Bxd6 23. Bxg8 fxe5 24. fxe5
Bxe5 25. Bxh7 b5 {and Black has only a slight edge, if any.}) 18... Be7 $1 {
Black quickly corrects his previous slip.} (18... h6 {comes to much the same
thing -- Black will have to play ...Be7 next move anyway to connect his Rooks.}
) 19. Ka2 {Now Black looks for targets in White's position and spots the
undefended pawn on f2. But how should he attack it?} 19... Nxf3 (19... h6 {
would keep a pesky Knight out of g5 permanently.}) 20. Bxf3 Rd2 {
Hitting a weak pawn.} (20... Rd4 {is also reasonable, with a similar set of
ideas. One point here is that White cannot save the pawn by} 21. f5 {because of
} 21... Rf4 {hitting the pawn on f5, the Bishop on f3, and (behind the Bishop)
the pawn on f2. White can save two of these, but not all three:} 22. Be4 Rxf2
23. Rag1 g6 24. f6 Bd8 25. Bd5 {Now Black would rather not play passively with
...Rf8, but fortunately he can counterattack:} 25... Bc7 $1 26. Ne4 Rf5 27. Ng5
Bxe5 28. Nxf7 Rf8 29. Be6+ Kc7 30. Bxf5 Rxf7 31. Re1 Bxf6 $19 {
Black's Bishop and three pawns should be worth more than White's Rook.}) 21.
Ne4 Rd4 22. Rac1 Rhd8 (22... b5 {
makes sense here, defending c4 firmly and intending ...Bb7.}) 23. Rc3 Kb8 (
23... b5 {is again very good.}) 24. Rg1 g6 25. Re1 b5 $1 {There we go!} 26.
Rce3 Bb7 27. Nc3 a6 {This is a simple way to hold onto the pawn.} (27... Bxf3
28. Rxf3 b4 {is another way to make things work. White is lost after} 29. axb4
cxb4 30. Ne2 Rd1 $19 {The threat of ...b3+ is too much for White, e.g.} 31.
Rxd1 Rxd1 32. b3 Rd2+ {picking up the Knight.}) 28. Bxb7 Kxb7 29. Kb1 Rxf4 {
White resigns} 0-1

