1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 Bb5 7. Bxb5+ Qxb5 8.
Nbd2 {This is an odd move, but one benefit of it is that White has the
possibility of playing Nb3 attacking c5. Black therefore avoids the
"automatic" ...Nc6 and puts the Knight on d7, where in fact it often goes in
this line, giving c5 some additional defense.} 8... Nd7 (8... Nc6 9. Nb3 {
gives Black little.}) 9. a4 (9. Nb3 Rc8 10. Qc2 Qa6 {
Staying on the diagonal leading to f1.} 11. Be3 cxd4 12. Bxd4 Ne7 13. a3 Ng6
14. Rd1 Be7 $15 {White is hampered by his inability to castle.}) 9... Qa6 {
Staying on the diagonal leading to f1, preventing White from castling since it
is against the rules to pass through check (as the King would passing through
the f1 square here) while castling.} 10. b3 {White is trying to play c4 here.}
10... cxd4 11. c4 Ne7 {
This Knight could recapture a pawn on d5 if White were to take there.} 12. O-O
d3 $5 {Oddly enough, this pawn proves hard to capture.} 13. Re1 (13. cxd5 Nxd5
{The threat of ...Nc3 is awkward to meet.} 14. Nc4 Nc5 $1 $17 {Renewing the
threat of Nc3, with the additional point that the pawn on b3 will be weak.
Black's pieces coordinate beautifully.}) 13... Rd8 14. Bb2 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nc6
16. Nd6+ $2 {
This check looks tempting, but in fact White cannot keep the pawn on d6.} (16.
Qxd3 {was a better try. Black is only a bit better after} 16... Ndxe5 17. Qe2
Nxc4 18. bxc4 Bb4 19. Bxg7 Rg8 20. Bf6 Bxe1 21. Bxd8 Bxf2+ 22. Qxf2 Nxd8 $15)
16... Bxd6 17. exd6 O-O {
King out of the way -- now we're ready for some action!} 18. Ba3 e5 19. b4 {
White threatens a nasty fork.} 19... Qc4 $1 {Black finds the chain of
weaknesses in White's control of the center: White has no control of the light
squares c4 and d5. These squares are, therefore, natural squares for Black's
pieces to take over.} 20. Nd2 $2 {
This move is too slow, allowing Black to build a massive center.} (20. Rc1 {
would also be met by} 20... Qd5 $1 $17) (20. Re3 {is a better try, e.g.} 20...
e4 21. Nd2 $1 Qd5 22. Nxe4) 20... Qd5 $1 21. Ne4 f5 $1 22. Ng5 h6 (22... e4 $1
{is also excellent right away.}) 23. Nf3 e4 {
Now it is plain that Black is winning.} 24. Nd2 Nd4 {White forfeits on time.
But it hardly matters, as Black has the tactical threat of ...Nc2 forking the
Rooks as well as the positional threat of ...Ne5 dominating the center and
preparing ...Rxd6-g6.} 0-1

