[Round "?"]
[White "Hoodoo"]
[Black "Volkov"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C02"]
[WhiteElo "1809"]
[BlackElo "2887"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2017"]
[PlyCount "52"]
[EventDate "2002.??.??"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 Bb5 {
All according to plan.} 7. O-O Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Qa6 9. Qc2 {
White chooses a new way to avoid the Queen exchange.} 9... Nd7 {It is very
on for the Knight to go to d7 rather than to c6 in this variation. For one
thing, that leaves open the possibility of ... Nge7-c6.} 10. Be3 Rc8 {
Black defends the pawn at c5 a third time so that he can play ...Ne7 without
losing the pawn.} 11. Qb3 Ne7 12. Nbd2 Nc6 (12... Nf5 {
is also very good here, intending to capture on e3.}) 13. Qd1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Be7
{Black does not neglect his development. Now is the right time to get castled.}
15. Nb3 O-O 16. Ng5 {
Perhaps White is trying to get this Knight out of the way of his f-pawn.} 16...
h6 17. Nh3 Nb4 18. Qg4 {
This threat is rather blunt, but that does not mean that Black can ignore it.}
18... Kh7 $1 19. Nf4 Nc2 20. Nh5 $2 {White tries to play tactical games while
his Rook on a1 is hanging. It doesn't work.} 20... g6 $1 21. Qh3 gxh5 {
There goes a piece.} 22. Qxh5 Nxe3 $1 {
Swapping off pieces is a time-honored way of breaking the force of an attack.}
23. fxe3 f5 $1 {That deals with the threat on f7.} 24. Rf3 {Last chance: White
tries a Rook lift. Black has to play thoughtfully here, since it is difficult
to defend the h6 square.} (24. exf6 Nxf6 {also leaves Black a piece up.}) 24...
Qe2 $1 {Pinning the Rook from behind.} 25. Raf1 Bg5 $1 26. R1f2 Bxe3 $1 {
White resigns} 0-1

